            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> You probably meant the last line to be\n\nYes, thanks!\n\n> I don't think this is a compile time error though. That forces everything to be fully typed which seems very restrictive.\n\nHmm I am not sure why should be very restrictive:\n\n1. Users who doesn't want to use subscripts they are not affected.\n2. For users who use subscripts would get error only on assignment that can introduce type information not in par with actual value like:\n   a. variable assignments: `cdef list[int] a = b`, where `b` is plain `list`\n   b. variable initialization: `cdef list[int] a = ['a', 'b']`\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> Assignment from subscripted to unsubscripted type should be still allowed: `cdef list a = b` (`b` is `list[int]`) \n\nThe user should have power to force it through via casting: `cdef list[int] a = <list[int]> b`...\n\nWith a. I don't see much problem. Point b. I think should be separate issue and requires diligent fine tuning to get it right.",
