        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Comments (rather than a coherent argument):\n\nIt's definitely stricter than `mypy` and `ty` seem to be. Neither of those complain.\n\nI think where you'll hit it most is at function boundaries (e.g. calling a function taking `list[float]` with a `list` argument, when it could just be that two functions are currently just using different levels of detail).\n\nThere's definitely cases where you legitimately start out with a general list actively do something to turn it into a specific list. e.g.\n\n```\ndef convert(input: list):\n    for n in range(len(input)):\n        input[n] = str(input[n])\n    output: list[str] = input\n```\n\nI know this is a very artificial way of writing and and most people would use a comprehension. And I know that a cast would be allowed. But it still doesn't feel wrong to me.\n\nType inference feels like a source of conflict? Is it an error to assign something that's untyped but has been inferred as a generic list to a fully typed list?",
